  "prompt": "When will I start the preparation of ilts?",
  "response": "The preparation time for the IELTS (International English Language Testing System) depends on your current level of English proficiency and your target score. Here are some general guidelines to help you decide when to start preparing:\n\n1. **Assessment of Current Level**: First, take a practice test to understand your current English proficiency. This will give you an idea of how much preparation you need.\n\n2. **Target Score**: Determine the score required for your goals (e.g., university admission, immigration). Different institutions and purposes require different scores.\n\n3. **Time Available**: Consider how much time you can dedicate to studying each week. If you're busy, you might need to start earlier to spread out your preparation.\n\n4. **Preparation Time Frame**:\n   - **Basic Level**: If you are at a beginner or lower-intermediate level, you might need six months to a year of preparation.\n   - **Intermediate Level**: If you are at an intermediate level, three to six months might be sufficient.\n   - **Advanced Level**: If you are already advanced, one to three months may be adequate.\n\n5. **Test Date**: Plan your preparation so that it concludes a few weeks before your intended test date, giving you time for review and practice.\n\nStart your preparation as early as possible to give yourself flexibility and reduce stress. Consistent, focused study is more effective than cramming. Consider enrolling in a preparation course, using official practice materials, and taking mock tests to track your progress.",
